No, apparently not. The creature hissed and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, Thassalin was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi let out a cry as she nearly lost her grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
""HOW CAN WE KILL HER?"" Nyssi shouted.
""AIM AT THEIR HEADS!""
""THAT WILL BE DIFFICULT!""
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, getting closer to the mountain he called home. The dark beast followed, but it became slightly panicky when it was hit from behind by a fire blast. It hadn't noticed that it wasn't alone. It became even more panicked as Thassalin slowed down and then swung his tail against its head, throwing it off course.
Knurrend and snarling, she shot upwards and spat into the air. Suddenly everything turned dark as if the monster had sucked all the light from the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly couldn't see anything anymore, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the tree branches before crashing into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he would fall and rushed right towards him, pulling the black cloud along with it.
“Kayel!” Tenuk screamed as he slid out of the cloud and began circling in the darkness below, looking for Nyssi and Thassalin. “What should we do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?”
Below, Nyssi struggled to stand up. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already at work. Unfortunately, the same did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn’t collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters ahead. Everything was pitch-black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in this shadow, something was screaming and screeching.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed beside Nyssi onto the ground, knocking her down. But she noticed that the tail only swung wildly around and didn’t attempt to hit her intentionally. The beast, or what little of it Nyssi could see and hear, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and disoriented it.
Plötzlich krachte ein Gewehrschuss durch den Nebel, und das Monster verstummte, kollabierte auf dem Boden und blieb regungslos liegen. Die Dunkelheit um sie herum löste sich auf und sie sahen, was geschehen war: Auf der Bestie stand Kayel, der heftig keuchend sein Gewehr hielt.
„Das war wohl... Der verrückteste Schattensprung, den ich je gemacht habe... Thanto kat'olon...“ Kabel rang nach Luft. Seine Augen glühten fast schwarz, und eine dunkle Energie umwirbelte seinen Körper. Aber während er noch sprach, kehrte die Farbe in seine Panzerung zurück, und seine Augen nahmen wieder ihre normale gelbe Farbe an.
Es dauerte einen Moment, bis Nyssi verstand, was geschehen war. Sie hatten alle gewusst, dass Kayel diese seltsamen Schattenkräfte besaß. Er nutzte sie selten, weil die meisten sie für unheimlich und ziemlich furchteinflößend hielten. Aber Nyssi hatte nicht gewusst, dass Kayel diese Kräfte auch in jeder Art von Dunkelheit einsetzen konnte. Und so wie Kayel sich benahm, war er offenbar auch ziemlich überrascht.
„Bist du ok?“, brach es aus Nyssi heraus.
„Ja, mir geht es gut. Ich habe etwas getötet, ich werde gleich wieder in Ordnung sein.“ Kayel betrachtete sein Werk, während Tenuk herabflog, neben ihm landete und wieder seine normale Spast-Form annahm.
Jetzt, wo sich die Bestie nicht mehr bewegte, konnten sie besser sehen, was sie war. Ihre Haut war rabenschwarz und schleimig, aber der Schleim blieb fest an ihrem Körper haften. Sie hatte vier Flügel und vier Extremitäten, die alle in langen, dünnen Klauen endeten, und zwei gerade Hörner standen von ihrem Schädel ab.
Bevor Tenuk und Kayel fragen konnten, was verdammt nochmal sie da vor sich hatten, kreischte etwas und sprang aus einem nahegelegenen Busch hervor. Es gelangte aber nicht bis zu ihnen, weil ein vertrautes Fahrzeug in seine Seite krachte und dafür sorgte, dass das Monster schlitternd vor Nyssis Füßen zum Stehen kam. Nyssi wollte nichts riskieren. Sie schnappte ihre Schrotflinte, feuerte ohne nachzudenken auf seinen Schädel und das Geschöpf starb an Ort und Stelle.
„Ups…“, murmelte Retvik vom Fahrersitz aus, bevor er unbeholfen den Motor ausschaltete und aus dem Truck stieg. „Ähm, das war eigentlich keine Absicht. Seid ihr alle in Ordnung?“
„Du hast die ganze Action verpasst,“ schimpfte Tenuk. „Wo warst du?“
„Ihr habt mich alle einfach stehen lassen. Ich bin gekommen, so schnell ich konnte…“, seufzte Retvik. „Darf ich fragen, was das für schreckliche Viecher sind?“
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had rallied again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not severely injured.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WERE PERISHING HERE AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED OUR GODS.”
“You mean that terrible god-monster-being that we… helped kill?” stammered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. MIGHT BE MORE OF THEM. BUT I COULD NOT SHOOT INTO THE HEAD. I DO NOT HAVE A FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, RIGHT?” Thassalin hobbled over to Kayel and patted his head. “THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO CAPABLE OF KILLING WHOLE UNIVERSES.”
“Ahm… thanks… I guess…”, shrugged Kayel. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the now definitely dead beasts. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began cutting off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards, she moved on to the next. But as Nyssi was just finishing up, the beasts suddenly burst into flames and turned into a pile of ashes in an instant. The same happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
“So, this is both practical and impractical at the same time…” Nyssi sighed. “But I do at least have the photos, hopefully.”
